    topicTitle: 'Challenge Mixed Questions',
    difficulty: 'Challenge',
    questionText: '(i) Show, by means of a diagram or otherwise, that\n\\( \\displaystyle\\sum_{i=1}^{n} i = \\displaystyle\\int_0^n x\\,\\mathrm{d}x + \\dfrac{n}{2}.  \\) [3 marks]\n\n(ii) Show similarly that\n\\( \\displaystyle\\sum_{i=1}^{n} i^2 > \\displaystyle\\int_0^n x^2\\,\\mathrm{d}x = \\dfrac{n^3}{3}.  \\) [3 marks]\n\n(iii) Show that\n\\( \\displaystyle\\sum_{i=1}^{n} i^2 < \\displaystyle\\int_1^{n+1} x^2\\,\\mathrm{d}x = \\dfrac{(n+1)^3 - 1}{3}.  \\) [4 marks]\n\n(iv) Deduce that\n\\( \\dfrac{n^3}{3} < \\displaystyle\\sum_{i=1}^{n} i^2 < \\dfrac{(n+1)^3}{3}  \\)\nand hence that \\( \\dfrac{1}{n^3}\\displaystyle\\sum_{i=1}^{n} i^2 \\to \\dfrac{1}{3} \\) as \\( n \\to \\infty \\). [4 marks]',
    marks: 14,
    examStyle: true,
    yearCreated: 2026,
    tags: [],
    workedSolution: {
      steps: [
        {
          stepNumber: 1,
          description: 'Prove part (i) using a staircase diagram.',
          workingLatex: '\\sum_{i=1}^{n} i = \\frac{n(n+1)}{2}, \\qquad \\int_0^n x\\,\\mathrm{d}x = \\frac{n^2}{2}',
          explanation: 'We know \\( \\sum_{i=1}^n i = \\frac{n(n+1)}{2} = \\frac{n^2}{2} + \\frac{n}{2} \\). Also \\( \\int_0^n x\\,\\mathrm{d}x = \\frac{n^2}{2} \\). Therefore \\( \\sum_{i=1}^n i = \\int_0^n x\\,\\mathrm{d}x + \\frac{n}{2} \\). Diagrammatically, the sum represents \\( n \\) rectangles of width 1 and heights \\( 1, 2, \\ldots, n \\) (right-endpoint rectangles for \\( y = x \\) on \\( [0, n] \\)). Each rectangle on \\( [i-1, i] \\) exceeds the area under \\( y = x \\) on that interval by a right triangle of area \\( \\frac{1}{2} \\). Summing \\( n \\) such triangles gives the excess \\( \\frac{n}{2} \\).'
        },
        {
          stepNumber: 2,
          description: 'Prove part (ii): lower bound using right-endpoint rectangles.',
          workingLatex: 'i^2 > \\int_{i-1}^{i} x^2\\,\\mathrm{d}x \\quad \\text{for each } i \\geq 1',
          explanation: 'On the interval \\( [i-1, i] \\), the rectangle of height \\( i^2 \\) (right endpoint) has area \\( i^2 \\). Since \\( x^2 \\) is increasing for \\( x \\geq 0 \\), we have \\( i^2 \\geq x^2 \\) for all \\( x \\in [i-1, i] \\), with strict inequality for \\( x < i \\). Therefore \\( i^2 > \\int_{i-1}^{i} x^2\\,\\mathrm{d}x \\). Summing from \\( i = 1 \\) to \\( n \\): \\( \\sum_{i=1}^n i^2 > \\int_0^n x^2\\,\\mathrm{d}x = \\frac{n^3}{3} \\).'
        },
        {
          stepNumber: 3,
          description: 'Prove part (iii): upper bound using left-endpoint rectangles.',
          workingLatex: 'i^2 < \\int_i^{i+1} x^2\\,\\mathrm{d}x \\quad \\text{for each } i \\geq 1',
          explanation: 'On the interval \\( [i, i+1] \\), the left-endpoint rectangle of height \\( i^2 \\) has area \\( i^2 \\). Since \\( x^2 \\) is increasing, \\( i^2 < x^2 \\) for all \\( x \\in (i, i+1] \\). Therefore \\( i^2 < \\int_i^{i+1} x^2\\,\\mathrm{d}x \\). Summing from \\( i = 1 \\) to \\( n \\): \\( \\sum_{i=1}^n i^2 < \\int_1^{n+1} x^2\\,\\mathrm{d}x = \\left[\\frac{x^3}{3}\\right]_1^{n+1} = \\frac{(n+1)^3 - 1}{3} \\).'
        },
        {
          stepNumber: 4,
          description: 'Deduce part (iv): the squeeze result.',
          workingLatex: '\\frac{1}{3} < \\frac{1}{n^3}\\sum_{i=1}^n i^2 < \\frac{(n+1)^3}{3n^3} = \\frac{1}{3}\\!\\left(1 + \\frac{1}{n}\\right)^{\\!3}',
          explanation: 'From parts (ii) and (iii), \\( \\frac{n^3}{3} < \\sum i^2 < \\frac{(n+1)^3-1}{3} < \\frac{(n+1)^3}{3} \\). Dividing by \\( n^3 \\): \\( \\frac{1}{3} < \\frac{1}{n^3}\\sum i^2 < \\frac{1}{3}(1+1/n)^3 \\). As \\( n \\to \\infty \\), the upper bound tends to \\( \\frac{1}{3} \\). By the Squeeze Theorem, \\( \\frac{1}{n^3}\\sum i^2 \\to \\frac{1}{3} \\). This can be verified with the known formula \\( \\sum i^2 = \\frac{n(n+1)(2n+1)}{6} \\): \\( \\frac{1}{n^3} \\cdot \\frac{n(n+1)(2n+1)}{6} = \\frac{(1+1/n)(2+1/n)}{6} \\to \\frac{2}{6} = \\frac{1}{3} \\).'
        }
      ],
      finalAnswer: '(i) Both sides equal \\( \\frac{n(n+1)}{2} \\). (ii)-(iii) Proved by comparing with right- and left-endpoint rectangles. (iv) \\( \\frac{1}{n^3}\\sum i^2 \\to \\frac{1}{3} \\) by the Squeeze Theorem.'
    }
